    },
    {
      "_id": "19",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "for the 2nd one, you are given that y=2X+3; and y=2x-5.  this is basically contradictory information, both can't be true.",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "19",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "20",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "to show this mathematically, you set (2x+3)=(2x-5), since both of these equal y, they are equal.",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "20",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "21",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "then, for 2x+3=2x-5, add 5 to both sides (if you add, subtract, multiply, or divide the same amount to 2 sides that are equal, they are both still equal.",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "21",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "22",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "2x+3+5=2x-5+5, which simplifies to 2x+8=2x.",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "22",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "23",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "then, subtract 2x from each side:  2x+3-2x=2x-2x",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "23",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "24",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "this simplifies to 3=0.  which is never true, so no solution!",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "3fa80047_line261",
      "sequence_id": "24",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "25",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "the other thing you can do for both problems is graph each solution on the graphs.  For the first 1 (infinite solutions), you would get 2 lines that are completely on top of each other.  For the 2nd one (no solutions), you would get 2 lines that never intersect (have no common point).",
